THOUGHT: The miscompilation occurs because the pass hoists zero-extend above an addition of a loop-carried i16 indvar and then performs the add in i32: transforming zext(add i16 iv, iv) into add i32 zext(iv), zext(iv). This changes semantics by eliminating i16 wrap. To fix, we should prevent widening across adds of the indvar unless NUW ensures no wrap. I will search for the widening code in SimplifyIndVar.cpp that rebuilds widened operations and add a guard to avoid hoisting zext across Add/Sub/Mul when this would alter wrap semantics, specifically when both operands originate from the same narrow IV without NUW. Then I will submit the patch.

```bash
applypatch << 'PATCH'
*** Begin Patch
*** Update File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/SimplifyIndVar.cpp
@@
   assert((Op->Opcode == Instruction::Add || Op->Opcode == Instruction::Sub ||
           Op->Opcode == Instruction::Mul) &&
          "Unexpected opcode");

   // One operand (NarrowDef) has already been extended to WideDef. Now determine
   // if extending the other will lead to a recurrence.
   const unsigned ExtendOperIdx = Op->Operands[0] == DU.NarrowDef ? 1 : 0;
   assert(Op->Operands[1 - ExtendOperIdx] == DU.NarrowDef && "bad DU");

+  // Avoid hoisting a zero/sign-extend across an arithmetic operation if doing so
+  // would change wrap semantics. In particular, for additions like
+  // zext(add iN %iv, %iv), widening to add(zext(%iv), zext(%iv)) computes in the
+  // wide type and loses the narrow wrap unless we can prove no unsigned/signed
+  // wrap. Guard this by requiring appropriate no-wrap on the original op when
+  // both operands are derived from the same narrow IV.
+  // This addresses miscompilations where the widened form produces a different
+  // constant exit value for loops that do not take the backedge.
+  if (Op->Opcode == Instruction::Add) {
+    Value *OpL = Op->Operands[0];
+    Value *OpR = Op->Operands[1];
+    // If both operands are the same narrow IV (or trivially derived from it),
+    // and we don't have NUW/NSW to guarantee no wrap, do not attempt to widen.
+    // Checking pointer equality to DU.NarrowDef is a conservative guard here.
+    bool BothFromSameNarrowIV = (OpL == DU.NarrowDef) && (OpR == DU.NarrowDef);
+    if (BothFromSameNarrowIV && !Op->IsNUW && !Op->IsNSW) {
+      return {nullptr, ExtendKind::Unknown};
+    }
+  }
+
   ExtendKind ExtKind = getExtendKind(DU.NarrowDef);
   if (!(ExtKind == ExtendKind::Sign && Op->IsNSW) &&
       !(ExtKind == ExtendKind::Zero && Op->IsNUW)) {
     ExtKind = ExtendKind::Unknown;

*** End Patch
